  "prompt": "What are the expectations of parents from their children?",
  "response": "Parents often have a range of expectations for their children, which can vary based on cultural, societal, and personal values. Here are some common expectations parents may have:\n\n1. **Academic Success**: Many parents hope their children will perform well in school, achieve good grades, and pursue higher education to secure a stable future.\n\n2. **Good Behavior and Discipline**: Parents generally expect their children to follow rules, show respect to others, and display good manners and ethical behavior.\n\n3. **Health and Well-being**: Ensuring that children lead healthy lifestyles, including proper nutrition, regular exercise, and mental well-being, is a priority for many parents.\n\n4. **Independence and Responsibility**: Parents often wish for their children to develop independence, take responsibility for their actions, and learn essential life skills.\n\n5. **Career and Financial Stability**: Many parents hope their children will choose stable and fulfilling careers, achieve financial independence, and make sound financial decisions.\n\n6. **Strong Relationships**: Parents may expect their children to build and maintain healthy, supportive relationships with family, friends, and eventually, their own partners and children.\n\n7. **Cultural and Moral Values**: Parents often pass down cultural, religious, and moral values, expecting their children to uphold and respect these traditions and beliefs.\n\n8. **Happiness and Fulfillment**: Above all, most parents wish for their children to lead happy, fulfilled lives, finding joy and satisfaction in their personal and professional endeavors.\n\n9. **Contribution to Society**: Some parents hope their children will contribute positively to society, whether through their careers, volunteer work, or other forms of community involvement.\n\n10. **Respect and Gratitude**: Parents may expect their children to show respect and gratitude towards them and others who have supported and cared for them throughout their lives.\n\nThese expectations can vary widely and may change over time as children grow and develop their own identities and goals. Open communication between parents and children can help align expectations and foster a supportive and understanding relationship.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
